column54: Scientists say that people's intelligence can grow with effort and practice because they believe that, after having observed the brains of active and inactive animals, the brain can grow like a muscle when presented with new stimuli. They then did a study on humans, in which they taught people who were not talented at juggling to juggle. After doing a brain scan, they noted that the parts of the brain that control juggling grew in those participants who learned how to juggle.
column60: It might affect their ability to learn in that those with a fixed mindset may not try as hard to learn new things beause they think that they will not make any progress, whereas those with a growth mindset may try to push themselves to solve new things because they believe that it will make them smarter.

column164: Dear friend, /  / The brain is incredibly useful. Things that you don't notice about your memory and what you see, hear, and feel are all controlled by different parts of the brain. The way you feel pain is important - if your parietal lobe didn't inform you, you could get badly burned without acknowledging the pain. Your brain is incredibly intelligent and fascinating - it does things "behind the scene" that we don't even realize. All the neurons and lobes help us form memories and acknowledge life experiences. With our brain, we are able to make daily decisions on what to wear, when to wake up, what to eat - to see each option and then, to make the decision. Without such functions, life would be incredibly difficult - we would get hurt easily without understanding that we are in pain. We wouldn't be able to see different opportunities and make a decision. Our brain is a mighty tool that we overlook many times!

column127: Dear Student,  /  / Although school can often be extremely discouraging and often doesn't test most people's strength effectively, there are strategies in order to improve and fix this terrible situation. Most importantly, practice is the most useful tactic in order to strengthen the mind. Although tedious and annoying, repetition the best way to strengthen the mind. Anyone who practices and does things repeatedly can succeed in whatever they try and do.

column164: Dear friend, / This may come off as a shocker, but the reality is, scientists do know a lot about the brain! In fact, they've even identified parts of the brain that specialize in many of the functions that we do each and every day. The brain is an amazing tool that allows us to do many things -- whether that be technical (solving math problems), creative (painting a picture), or even just letting our imaginations run wild as we read a book. Different parts of the brain controls different functions. For instance, you use your cerebellum to stay balanced when...you tight rope or do one-legged exercise stretches. You also use your hippocampus to help you remember what you learned in class. Unfortunately, when parts of the brain are damaged, life can get a bit harder because the parts of the brain that once specialized in certain functions are now unable to perform what they're meant to do. As a result, a person may lose the ability to do certain things. For example, someone may have their speech patterns affected when the part of the brain that specializes in speech is damanged. but looking at the bright side, it's very possible that other parts of the brain can take over the function that was lost, and in time, the speech patterns can be restored.

column60: If someone has a fixed mindset, they will be convinced that they are at their maximum level of learning when faced with new material. column75: I would tell my friend : Learning is a continuous process, with no limit. Therefore, believing that you have reached your limit is a silly idea. Such a mindset is called a fixed mindset, and that can prevent you from getting smarter because you refuse to see beyond your current abilities. By recognizing that you can continue to learn and absorb knowledge, you will gradually develop a growth mindset: one that will help you get smarter.  / For example, someone takes an exam, and notices that he/she got a lot of questions wrong. If he/she is like you, then he/she will give up, thinking, "that's as smart as I'm going to get". Do you see how hard it is to want to study when your thought process is like that?  / Now, if he/she had a growth mindset, he/she would take those mistakes and learn from them, study the topics closer and better, and eventually ace the next exam that the material appears on!  / So, clearly, you should not get discouraged every time you see a bad score or grade. In fact, you should use it as motivation for you to do better next time! You are plenty smart, but smartness is never concretely defined. It is up to you to keep pushing its limit.

column54: The scientists believe that people's intelligence can grow and get better with effort. The first reason is that when you push your brain to learn challenging things such as language, skills, and more the brain is able to develop to new levels that was not done before. Another reason is that the brain is forced to make connections when placed in challenging environments. The brain thus develops because it fosters connections. As these connections grow, the brain becomes stronger and more capable of deductive reasoning. Our brains welcome challenge because that is the reason continuous development is made possible. Eventually, with hard work and a willingness to accept challenges, our brains can develop more fully and we can accomplish what we never thought to be possible.
column60: Both the "fixed mindset" and the "growth mindset" attempt to explain the phenomenal workings of the human brain. I believe that each mindset can affect a person's intelligence and ability to learn and there are pros and cons to each. For example, those with fixed mindset often believe that intelligence is fixed and that hard work and acceptance of challenge will not change the outcome. They strongly believe there isn't much that can be done to culture the brain into a more complex and capable one. As a result, they often do not rise up to the challenge because they feel that the challenge will not play any benefit for them. At the same time, I believe that "fixed mindset" of intelligence can increase confidence necessary for excellence amongst individuals. If a person knows that he is naturally talented at something, he or she will possess the confidence necessary to overcome discouragement. I believe that those with the "growth mindset" are more willing to rise to the challenge and foster their growth. With their believe that the brain becomes stronger through exercise (like muscles), they are more willing to pursue goals that may seem far fetched. at the same time, such mindset can also discourage when one person sees another excelling more at something.
column75: Dear Louise,  /  / I know that schoolwork has been tough and you feel that you are incapable of accomplishing what you want to accomplish in academics. I am writing to you to remind you not to feel discouraged. It seems that at times, there are people who grasp the concepts better than you do or work faster than you do. However, i say don't be discouraged by this. Rather than having a "fixed mindset," it's important to keep a "growth mindset." There are so many examples of those who seemed to be behind, but worked really hard to become on top. For example, look at the thousands of athletes in the Olympics. I am sure that not every person in the Olympics was the fastest in every race. Yet, the believed strongly that with increased practice and challenge they could do better. Another example is my friend Shivani. Shivani's weakest subject in class was math. She started the class out with a C+ on her first test. However, she continuously practiced until she was able to do every question and approach any type of question thrown at her. Eventually, she was able to earn a A in what she she believed was her weakest subject. So, I say don't worry. You can do this. Just face the challenge head on and I promise you will improve.  /  / Best,  / Kaitlyn

column153: The brain has many important cells, called neurons. These neurons essentially carry the important information that is relayed to the brain through the various lobes. Because I have class registrations this week, my frontal lobe will help me in making decisions about what classes to take. The parietal lobe will help me this week when I am cooking. Finally, the temporal lobe is responsible for hearing, and thus it will help me when I am playing the piano. column164: Dear Friend, / Hello. I know that you think the brain is a total mystery and that people don't know anything about it. However, I am writing this letter to inform you that this idea of yours is actually false, and that many people, in fact, do know much about the brain, including me. In fact, I want to tell you what I personally have just learned about the brain. /  / First of all, the brain is separated into various lobes. The brain is still one organ, but with various parts to it internally. Much like a house is one structure, even though there are many rooms inside it with various functions, the brain is one organ with many different functions. But before I begin talking about these individual functions, I want to first introduce neurons to you. You do know that cells are the essential unit to humans. In the brain, these special cells called neurons carry information and all the data that allows us to be who we are and think what we think. These neurons are carried through dendrites. The neuron relay chain is shaped much like the branches of a tree. These branches are called dendrites, which is "branches" in Greek. These dendrites then touch other dendrites and relay information to other parts of the body. Now that this has been introduced, I want to tell you about the different functions of the brain. The human brain is relatively large compared to those of other animals. The frontal lobe is in the front, and is responsible for all the "thinking" we do, such as decision making, critical thinking, and the storage of long-term memory. The parietal lobes are responsible for our teaching. When our hands stroke soft fabric, we don't automatically know that the fabric is soft. Instead, the texture is relayed as information in neurons through dendrites to the rest of our brain, and in the parietal lobe, this information is then converted into a texture that we are familiar with. Thus, without the parietal lobe, we wouldn't have any feeling. The occipital lobe is responsible for sight, and is located in the back of our head. Our eyes are actually seeing things very blurry. When the light enters our eyes, it is then relayed through nerves to our brain's occipital lobes. It is then that our brain is able to identify the light and objects that entered our eyes and transform them into sight and objects that we can distinguish and recognize. Thus, even if your eyes are working fine, if you don't have a proper occipital lobe, chances are that you won't be able to see anything. The temporal lobe is responsible for our hearing, and much like the other lobes in our brain, transform and identfity the information in the form of neurons that first enter our brain through the ears. /  / As you can see, there is so much information about the brain. I only relayed to you a tad bit of what I learned just now; there is so much more that can still be learned! /  / Sincerely, / Your Friend Kyeihong

column153: Memory is operated by several different parts of the brain. The hippocampus is the part of the brain that transfers memories form short to long term. The thalamus stores spatial memories. column159: The occipital lobe is the part of the brain that let's us process visuals. It contains the primary visual cortex. The occipital lobe is essential for my everyday life, because it literally let's me see the world. It'll help me see what I'm doing. It'll help me see when I wake up to put my cloths on, when I drive to work, when I step on the train, and pretty much everything including the words I am now typing on this screen. /  / The frontal lobe is the part of the brain that helps me make decisions and think about consequences of actions. It is the part of the brain the rationalized and thinks about whether something is right or wrong, good or bad. It helps me explore thought, and helps me connect things. It's important in my everyday life because it takes consequences into account. It also contains the primary motor cortex, which literally allows me to move my body through the transmissions of neurons. It will help me to plan my classes this week. It will help me think about what I want to take, and the good and bad consequences of taking each class that I'm considering. It also literally helps me move my physical body so that I can physically sign up for my classes by clicking on my computer mouse.  /  / The parietal lobe helps me process sensory information. It has two primary hemispheres. The left processes functions in language and methematics, etc. The right processes spatial relationships. My parietal lobe will help me do my Stats HW this week. I will need to use the left part of my parietal lobe to understand my Stats, and the relevance of each number and formula.  /  / The temporal lobe processes auditory information and allows me to hear things. It helps in processing both speech and vision as well. I will use my temporal lobe this week at work. When my boss tells me to do something, I will be able to process what he is saying, and then go about doing the task.
column164: Dear friend, /  / The brain is a complicated thing to understand, but in trying to understand it, you are actually using your brain. The brain has four primary structures called lobes. Each lobe serves and integral function. The temporal lobe allows you to hear and process sound. The occiupital lobe allows you to process visuals and see. The Parietal lobe allows you to understand information and process spacial aspects. And finally the frontal lobe allows you to think about actions and consequences. It basically processes all conscious thought. When people use their brain, all parts of the brain work in unision. For example, when you are playing basketball each part of the brain is doing something different. The occipital lobe is allowing you to see where you are dribbling. The temporal lobe allows you to hear the request and advice of your teammates and coach. The fronal lobe allows you to think about what you want to do. And the consequences of shooting as opposed to passing. And the parietal lobe allows you to process the score and how much space you have between you and the defender. Life can be hard when different parts of the brain don't work, because each part plays such an intergral function. For example, a defect in the occipital lobe could several limit, confuse, or even destory your vision which would have a devastating effect on your sight. If you can't see, life would be very difficult. The same applies to hearing. If the frontal or parietal lobe was damaged you might have a lot of confusion in your life and have a very difficult time processing simple and complex things.

column159: My occipital lobe will help me read my Stats homework in order to do my homework, plan my outfits for the week, and make sure I don't look like a mess before leaving the house.  The parietal lobe will help me gauge whether it is too hot or too cold and if I have dressed appropriately.  The temporal lobe will help me interact with my students, remember my morning routine, how to get to my job, and so forth. Finally the frontal lobe will help me decide what answer to choose for my stats homework and how to plan my class schedule for next year.
column164: The front brain is broken into four parts that help you accomplish different tasks: the occipital, parietal, temporal, and frontal lobe.  The occipital lobe helps you with processing what your eyes see, kinda like photoshop.  If this part of the brain is damaged, even if your eyes work fine, you could still go blind.   The parietal lobe helps with touch and sensations--it can help you tell if something is soft, warm, hot, or painful.  The temporal lobe can help you with speech, choosing the right word, and memory.  If it is damaged, you may not be able to speak properly as you cannot retrieve the correct word.  The frontal lobe helps you make decisions.

column60: Someone who has a Fixed Mindset will have a more defeatist attitude toward learning difficult material, thus realizing what they believe about their intelligence and decreasing their ability to learn. Someone who has a Growth Mindset will try harder at changing what they believe is possible to change. In doing so, they will most likely improve their ability to learn and become more intelligent.
column75: Having the right mindset can change the way you learn and affect your intelligence. If you have a Fixed Mindset and believe that intelligence cannot be changed, you will adopt a defeatist attitude toward learning and give up easily when confronted with a difficult task. This lack of effort will never grow or improve your ability to learn new material. I used to play the flute. Because I believed that I did not have musical talent, I often avoided practicing. Over the year, while everyone else in the orchestra mastered new scales and techniques, my ability to play stayed the same because I thought it would be a waste for me to invest time and energy in something that was never going to change. Eventually I quit the flute. If I'd had a Growth Mindset, I would have consistently dedicated a certain amount of time to practicing, believing that with every mistake I made and corrected, I was strengthening the muscles in my fingers and the connections in my brains--conditioning myself to better grasp the tunes and patterns of the music.  / If you have a Growth Mindset, you believe that intelligence can be changed, that with effort and practice, the muscle that is your brain can strengthen and develop over time. I did poorly on my first math midterm in college. For the second midterm, I began studying earlier in the week and pulled an allnighter, covering piles and piles of scratch paper with practice problems from the book and from lectures. This, I believed, strengthened my ability to utilize logic and reasoning to go about solving the problems. I ended up with nearly 100% on the midterm.  / Having the right mindset can truly affect how one handles difficult situations. That attitude in itself can make a difference in the results.

column75: You have the potential to perform much better in school. You have what is called a "fixed mindset" where you believe that people cannot increase their intelligence by working harder or learning new things. But you are wrong. Having a "growth mindset" on the other hand, is where you believe that with hard work and by trying to reach out and learn new and challenging things, your brain will develop faster and increase in intelligence. That is what you need. If you have a growth mindset, you will approach challenges instead of just trying to skim by the edge. You will be encouraged to reach out to a teacher or even a peer for help with stuff that you don't know. This in turn, will increase your knowledge of new, harder concepts which you would have just overlooked and avoided. There was a study where 2 twins who started off with the same intelligence level, making the same mistakes and having the same amount of knowledge of math. However, one twin had a "fixed mindset" while the other student had a "growth mindset". The twin who believed they couldn't do anything about their level of intelligence skipped over problems that were difficult and just worked with the easiest problems. The other twin always looked for the right answers and explanations to problems they didn't understand and seeked challenging questions. Initially, people thought the first twin was smarter because she finished everything so easily and quickly, but in the end the second twin came out with a more developed and stronger brain because she had conquered concepts and gained a deeper understanding of math than her twin sister had.

column164: Dear friend, /  / While I do share your concern about the complexity of the brain, the functions are outlined by the different parts of it. There are 4 parts to the brain: the occipital lobe, the frontal lobe, the temporal lobe, and the parietal lobe. All serve different functions that control your senses such as sight, touch, memory, etc. Within the brain, signals are transmitted to process information. This is done through neurons. Neurons are comprised of different parts such as axons, dendrites, the soma, etc. Dendrites are branch-like that receive signals from axons to transmit information in the brain. Should one part function abnormally, your brain could be partially impaired and thus limit your ability to process all information necessary.

The more that we challenge our mind to learn, the more our brain cells grow. Then, things that we once found very hard or even impossible to do — like solving statistic problems — seem to become easy. The result is a stronger, smarter brain.

column164: The brain is the mastermind behind all of your actions, emotions, decisions, things you see; it is pretty much in charge of everything in your life. However, the brain doesn't do all of these tasks for you as a whole. It is split up into many different sections, each with a different function that is applicable to you in everyday life. There are four parts of the brain, the frontal lobe, parietal lobe, occipital lobe, and the temporal lobe. The occipital lobe is in charge of giving you vision and sight. It converts the very complicated information you see from your eyes into information to be interpreted by other parts of your brain so you understand what you are seeing. If your occipital is injured, you may lose your eye sight even though your eyes might still be fine. The temporal lobe is in charge of sense perception, memory and speech. It is the part that helps you feel touch, smell etc. It is also the part that allows you to understand what your friends are saying, and helps you formulate words that you say in return. It also stores information, creating memories. The parietal lobe is in charge of movement, orientation and recognition. It helps you move around and give you the sense of where you are as well as being able to recognize. And finally, the frontal lobe. It is the part of the brain that allows you to make decisions and feel emotion. This is the part of the brain that will help you with your logical thinking, problem solving skills, and planning. If this part is damaged then you will have trouble with movement, making decisions and feeling emotions.

column164: The brain is divided into several lobes, the parietal, temporal, occipital, and frontal lobes. Each lobe is responsible for a different function. For example, the temporal lobe is responsible for auditory perception and speech while the frontal lobe, which is located in the forebrain, allows us to think and make judgments. Even though the brain is divided into different hemispheres and sulcus, the connections and synapses within the brain is all interconnected as they all share information. For example, the brain is the largest part of the central nervous system and information from all parts of the brain is sent down the spinal cord to make movements, reflexes, or take any action. Therefore, damage to one part of the brain may have serious effects on the whole body. Although our brain is considered to be plastic, demyelination of neurons or any lesions to the brain can permenantly impair the way our brain and body functions together.

column117: Scientists believe that the brain functions similarly to a muscle, meaning that as you exercise your brain and focus on solving problems, your brain grows just like how a muscle grows if you lift weights. More complex and novel problems give better results, better growth, in the same way that lifting progressively heavier weights builds muscle. However, performing the same tasks over and over again tends to not yield any results.  /  / Scientists believe people aren't necessarily "math" or "not math" people, it's just that some people have had more practice than others. We all start out not knowing math, but some people get better than others based on exposure and practice. This notion extends to all types of activities, such as juggling. Studies show that people who learned juggling grew certain parts of their brain that affect motor skills. Learning math and how that affects the brain works in a similar fashion. Good strategies also affect how the brain grows. So if you want better math abilities, practice practice practice!
column122: When I started golfing, I was bad. Swinging a club didn't make sense to me. I felt awkward and as a result my swing was awkward and not fluid at all. It took hours of practice to get to a point where I became comfortable swinging a club and that translated into a more fluid motion. For practice, I had a coach that taught me the fundamentals--how to grip the club, where to focus my eyes, how to position my feet, how to turn properly, etc. I would practice for an hour or two each day, going over the fundamentals until everything became clear. I'd go to the driving range to hit balls and experiment with different strategies. Sometimes I'd put my feet farther forward, sometimes a little farther back. Sometimes I'd grip the club slightly different until I found something that truly worked. I ended up playing golf for years, but it took months and months of dedication and persistence to get good. I took what I learned on the driving range and put it to use on the course. If I made mistakes, I made note of what I did wrong and then I tried my best to correct them. I kept all my scorecards, and if my scores weren't improving regularly, I'd figure out what I needed to change. It was mostly a lengthy trial and error period but eventually I kept playing and got better and better. Just becoming so used to swinging a club helped immensely. The rigorous practice of doing something over and over again kind of re-wired my brain and everything became second nature, like it was a part of me.
column127: You're not dumb, you just need a new set of skills. That's what everything boils down to: skills. If you can't do something, you need a new skill. So, to get a new skill you need to practice. But not only do you need to practice, you need to practice correctly. Only good practice brings good results, the rest is useless and won't do you any good. If you want to learn math, start small. Do basic algebra problems for a while. Whenever something gets difficult, figure out what you're doing wrong, digest that information and try again. The important thing is not to give up. You need to have a structured program in order to progress. It's a process, sometimes a long one. Do something like 25 math problems a day and make sure that they get harder and harder each time. If a weight lifter starts bench pressing at 100 lbs and by the start of the next week he's benching 120, then you should be doing 35 math problems that are more complex than the last set. Keep doing this and increase the difficulty. Work your way up to Algebra 2, then the other divisions.

column164: Dear friend, /  / I believe it is mistaken to believe that people have not learned a bit about the brain. Researchers and scientists have discovered many of the fundamental tasks the brain achieves on a daily basis. The brain is able to process a ton of information passively, and subdivides tasks between different physical regions of the brain, called lobes. There are four lobes to a human or general animal brain. Each lobe has a specialized function, and damage to any of these lobes can result in blindness (occipetal), being mute or unable to understand speech (temporal love), impacted decision making (frontal lobe), or sense of touch (parietal lobe). The neural network that is your brain has been researched a little, but scientists are still working to unlock its mysteries, because in my opinion it's the organ that makes us who we are. /  / Your friend

column164: Dear Friend, / While the brain may seem like a mystery, scientists have made many amazing discoveries about how the brain functions, its capabilities when healthy, and limitations when damaged. Scientists have divided the brain into four separate regions or "lobes," that each serve a different purpose. These lobes work in conjunction to make the body function. If one area of the brain is damaged, the entire body may not necessarily stop working, but certain parts will--the parts that are associated with that lobe. For example, the occipital lobe addresses messages from the eyes, so if it incurs damage, a person will be without sight even though their eyeballs are still sending messages to the brain. The messages are never successfully delivered because the occipital lobe has been damaged. Due to the complexity of the brain, there is still much to be explored and learned. However scientists have already learned a great deal about how the brain functions, which is useful information because it enhances medical, psychological, and popular knowledge.

column75: Your level of intelligence has more to do with the effort you put forth than your base line level of intelligence. Everyone starts out at their baseline of intelligence, what they are born with naturally. However, people with a fixed mindset do not believe that this level can increase in any way. Thus, they take mistakes as only showing their limitations. To do better in school, you should change your mind set to a one of growth. Look at mistakes as a chance to learn. Examining why you made those mistakes will strengthen the connections in your brain and this new information will be more throughly learned. Doing this, you will be more encouraged to attempt new challenges which will lead to more mistakes. Every mistake slowly increasing your intelligence level. Therefore, with the growth mindset you will increase your intelligence from the level you were born with. Growth can always overcome stagnation. Even if you are born with less intelligence than someone with a fixed mindset, if you believe that your intelligence can grow and if you embrace your mistakes as opportunities to become smarter, you will surpass anyone who has a fixed mindset in intelligence. Your level of intelligence is up to you, the effort you put forth, and how you look at the mistakes you make.

column127: Hey Neil, /  / I know you've been strugging with school recently; I also know you've been questioning your own intelligence because of your struggles. I just want you to know that struggle or even failure means you are not smart. Being smart is failing and then learning from those failures. Keep taking challenges--these challenges will help your brain grow and strengthen, even if you don't succeed smoothly the first few tries. You can't half-heartedly try to blunt force your way through learning, though. You have to really think about concepts you learn about--study them from all angles in your mind to find and fully understand different strategies of dealing with those concepts. Your brain is like a muscle--and you have to train it in the right way to win the Olympics. You can't swim half heartedly fifty meters out into the pool if you want to win gold at the 100 meter free style. Remember that you have friends and teachers who are there to explain concepts to you if you need help. Although I don't want to categorize anything as "stupid," I have to say students who don't take advantage of asking others for help come pretty close. Pride or indifference, whatever the reason, one of the smartest things you can do is ask others for help if you don't understand. Not knowing does not make one any less smart. It is not doing anything about not knowing that may be on the not-so-smart side. /  / Either way, you can always turn to me if you need anyone to talk too! I'm here for you!

column164: The brain is a complex organ, and something that you use in every moment of every day. It is divided into 4 parts that control different functions. The occipital lobe is responsible for vision. Everything your eyes see, is filtered by your brain. Think of the brain as fine tuning a very blurry image. The temporal lobe is responsible for all the auditory things you hear. In addition to allowing you to hear, it allows you to respond to auditory signals, like someone calling your name. The parietal lobe is responsible for the sense of touch. When something touched you, the signals travel through your nerves, through your spine to your brain and your brain is what tells you if something is soft, or rough, or painful, etc. Lastly the frontal lobe is where all of the actual logic and decision making come into play. You can think of it like this; the temporal, parietal, and occipital are you senses, and the frontal is what you use to reason. You can imagine how if these lobes arent properly working, how damaging that would be to what you experience every day.

column159: The occipital lobe will be helpful in allowing me to comprehend the presentations my professors project on the screen and the text in my textbook. column164: Hi friend, /  / I know you think the brain is a total mystery -- but the truth is, scientists know quite a bit about the brain. We don't really realize how complex the whole system is since most of its functions come naturally to us. however, there are a bunch of different parts to the brain that allow us to live out our everyday lives. /  / For example, the forebrain contains the following lobes: frontal, occipital, temporal, and parietal. They each deal with something unique -- and do so almost instantaneously.  /  / The frontal lobe helps us make decisions: like what to wear one day, or what advice we should give to a friend in need. The occipital lobe deals with vision; damage to the lobe could lead to blindness, even if your eyes are working fine. It's crazy to think that what our eyes see is actually really difficult to understand until our brains process it. The temporal lobe involves hearing and memory. Without this lobe, you wouldn't understand your professor or comprehend or sing to the latest hit on the radio. Finally, the parietal lobe: you know your favorite soft sweater? That's the work of the parietal lobe. The same thing goes for the weather; without the parietal lobe, you wouldn't know what kind of day it is, and you wouldn't feel pain either, which is really dangerous. /  / As you can see, the brain is complex -- but it's not a complete mystery.

column164: What makes our bodies tick can be confusing to those of us who haven't studied it directly, but there are millions out there who actually have studied it, and have come up with answers!  I think we often think about being either "left" or "right"-brained, but what we often don't realize is that we can break that down even further....and then break *that* down even further.  How about we start with just the first breakdown, so that it's easier to understand?   There are 4 sections ("lobes" to our brains.  We've got the frontal lobe, that enables us to do things like make plans, and remember where we put our keys (short-term memory).  The temporal lobe helps us remember things like not only how to talk, but what each word means.  The parietal lobe helps us understand that we are feeling something like a cool breeze, or the tickle of a feather - think of it like the "touch" sensor.  The occipital lobe helps our eyes to actually "see" and figure out what the images are in front of our eyes.  It's located towards the back of our skull, but in a direct line with our eyes.  If we damage the occipital lobe of our brain, we can actually go blind - even if our eyes themselves are working perfectly!

Scientists have observed that the first group of animals only ate and slept all day. The second group sought different ways to play with their toys and ways to get along with the animals they were exposed to. The second group were able to "grow" their brain, meaning that their brains were heavier than the first group.
column122: My personal experience actually involves math. During high school, I never had a great interest in math. When I entered Berkeley, I took a math adjunct class that was offered at the Student Learning Center on campus. The class was centered around learning strategies on how to study, understand, and then apply those techniques to solving math problems. From that class, I learned what I was doing wrong. Instead of being taught to understand the "why" and "how" behind the formulas and concepts, I focused on memorizing the formulas and examples. Therefore, when I was given a problem where the wording was a different from what I expected, I would not know what to do. This class changed my whole strategy and now I focus on understanding the concepts and ideas behind each problem and as a result my math skills have greatly improved and math is now one of my favorite subjects.

column75: Hey Samantha, /  / I know you have been struggling with math, and that you feel that your lack of skill is genetic, but I know you are smarter than that, and all you need is a little extra practice to get better. Instead of thinking it was genetic, I remember changing my attitude towards my lack of skill and just practiced by reading all sorts of books--especially more difficult readings for my age at the time. Overtime, I expanded my vocabulary tremendously and I made less and less grammatical errors.  /  / In the end, by challenging yourself to leave your comfort zone, and by learning from your mistakes, with practice, you can make yourself better at math. This is something you can control, and whatever outcome you want is completely in your hands. /  / I wish you the best, / XXXXX

column54: The brain is a muscle formed by the connections between neurons. Scientists performed a study in which they observed the neural activity of people who tried to practice juggling; sections of the brains of these people had grown connections that control juggling (probably in the area of the brain dedicated to hand-eye coordination, spatial movement and recognition). The more you practice something, the more connections are formed. /  / Conversely, if you were once adept at something but you don't practice it for a long time, the connections often become inaccessible.
column60: Someone with a Growth Mindset would be more persistent and ultimately more successful in their endeavor to improve their intelligence, because they know that dedicating time to the abilities they want to hone pays off. /  / Someone with a fixed mindset would have lower motivation. People with a fixed mindset and who think themselves to be average would see no point in trying to improve or practice much if it doesn't yield a significant payoff. People with a fixed mindset and who think themselves to be talented would take their skills for granted and expect their skills to show with little effort.
column75: Hey friend, /  / I've noticed that you haven't been really motivated to work hard on schoolwork lately, and it seems to be because you think you're bad at it, right? /  / (friend nods) /  / Actually whenever I see you try to study I see a lot of potential! You're really creative and driven outside of class (cite examples in which I saw them exercise their creative capabilities and drive), and sometimes I see that whenever I discuss things we covered in class with you. And I get excited because, you see, it's proven that if you work hard then no matter how difficult the subject is at first, your brain learns its way around - no, through it. See thinking isn't something that's static, it's more fluid, reinforced by connections between neurons in the brain. When you learn something new connections are formed, and when you re-visit it you strengthen those bonds and make them last longer. This means that every single second that you spend studying a subject is worth it! /  / So you know what I think? I think you should go home today and look up studies on growth mindsets if you don't believe me. Right now you have a fixed mindset, and it's impeding your ability to achieve your potential in schoolwork, and that saddens me as a friend because I know you're capable of so much more. /  / Sorry to um, lecture you, I'll step down from the soapbox now. But really, just work hard (pats friend on shoulder) very few of us here were born geniuses.

column164: The brain is a fascinating object of study. First of all, we know of its existence through X-rays (technology) and cadavers where scientists have physically grasped the brain. What you must know about the brain is that it is the most important organ in our body, for it serves as the mastermind behind all our actions, thoughts, feelings, and every other thing you can think of. Our ability to plan out schedules or study concepts for an upcoming test can be attributed to the many different parts of the brain working in harmony with one another. Our sense of smell, touch, hearing, memory retention, sight, and so forth, are only feasible because our brains contain millions of little neurons which transmit electrical signals via dendrites and axons that connect these neurons. After acknowledging the many vital bodily functions that are possible because the brain is what it is, we can infer that any minor damage to such a delicate, cohesive structure can result in serious damage. For example, imagine if you got into a car accident which led to a serious head injury. Such a fatal accident may damage the sensitive areas of the brain and only if a few neurons or areas of the brain are hurt, communication between brain and body will be deterred, therefore creating the possibility of going blind, deaf, mute, and so on.

column164: Dear Friend, /  / The brain of course, is used to do every task you do in your everday life. These include driving, eating, sleeping, or even picking out what to wear! However, the brain isn't just one big thing that does its stuff. Like a computer, it has many parts which each help you do different tasks. For example, a part of your brain called the temporal lobe is responsible for how you hear and comprehend the things you talk about with your friends and others. You might think that your vision is completely dependent on your eyes, but in actuality, a part of your brain called the frontal lobe has a big part in what you see as well! There is even a part of your brain where you could go blind if it stops working, even if your eyes are perfectly fine. Naturally, if one or more of these parts in your brain are damaged, it could be very hard to do many things in your everday life, so it is important to understand how to take care of your brain and to do that, you must first understand how the brain works.

column164: Hi Dear! / It is not really odd that you think brain is totally mysterious. However, the development of scientific knowledge has discovered many important aspects of brains.  / First, the brain is divided into four dfiferent section. The frontal lobe, temporal lobe, parietal lobe, and occipital lobe.  / The frontal lobe is the ultimate decider of everything! It helps us to make decisions, process our thinking and control other parts of the brain. The temporal lobe looks after the processing of information that we hear, and manage our memory system. The parietal lobe helps us to feel what we touch and sense through our sensory neurons. Lastly, the occipital lobe is responsible for the processing of information we gained from what we see. The raw information that we attain through our eyes is actually very unorganized and random. Therefore, we need occipital lobe to identify the information that we need among the many pieces of information we have. If any of these parts of brain is damaged, they will no longer function properly that we may lose ability to make decision through reasoning, hearing, seeing, and feeling. The brain system is definitely complex but many more parts of it is getting uncovered! So look for the news!

column153: The forebrain is the largest part of the brain as well as the part that is studied most by scientists. It is divided into four different lobes called frontal, temporal, parietal, and occipital. The frontal lobe is in charge of high-level actions, such as making decisions and controlling emotions. The temporal lobe controls hearing and languages as well as memory. The parietal lobe deals with touch and lastly, the occipital lobe controls the human vision.
column159: The occipital lobe will help me read the books I need to read for my final next Thursday. column164: Dear Irene, /  / I remember how you told yesterday that there is a lack of research and studies on the brain. I'm writing a letter to you because I just found out that scientists actually have a great amount of knowledge about the brain and that they believe it is one of the most important and useful organ that humans have. /  / To put it simply, it controls everything that you do. For example, when we went shopping yesterday, the brain was the one that helped you browse through the stores, listen to your favorite song in that one store, feel the softness of the sweater you got, and decide on which dress to get. The brain is divided into three main parts: hindbrain, midbrain, and forebrain. Among these, the forebrain is the most important and is composed of 4 different lobes. The occipital lobe controls your vision, the parietal lobe controls touch, the temporal lobe is in charge of hearing and learning/understanding languages as well as memory, and the frontal lobe executes decision making and emotions.  /  / As you can see, the brain controls everything we do. If any parts of the brain were to get damaged, our lives would be changed forever. I learned today that an injury on your occipital lobe can lead to blindness, even if one's eyes are perfectly normal. So I hope that you learned a little more about the functions and the usefulness of the brain from this letter. /  / Best, / Taylor

column164: Dear Friend, /      Prepare yourself for a quick lecture from Brain 101.  Our brains can be divided into four sections, or lobes.  They are the Frontal, Parietal, Occipital, and Temporal lobes. The frontal lobe is located in the front (Frontal, front, makes sense right?) of your brain.  It handles things like basic motor skills, and controls your judgement and emotions.The temporal lobe is located on the side of your brain, near your ears and temples (Temporal, temples, you get it?). The temporal lobe is in charge of your memory and hearing.  The Occipital lobe is located in the back of your brain and controls vision (Occipital, optics, they sound somewhat similar).  Lastly the parietal lobe is located on top of your brain and it integrates sensory input from touching and feeling, so you can figure out what you're touching and feeling (unfortunately, i haven't been able to determine any obvious mnemonics to assist you in remembering the location or tasks of the parietal lobe).  One thing i want you to understand is that damage to a lobe makes it difficult to complete its tasks adequately.  So if you fall backwards and hit the back of your head and damage your occipital lobe, you might suddenly find it very difficult to see. If you're jumping on the bed and you still haven't gotten off even though your mom told you to, and consequently you smash your head on the ceiling, you might find it difficult to feel things from then on due to damage to your parietal lobe. As you can see, it is very important to keep your brain safe as it does a lot for you.  Or if you really must damage your brain, at least damage a lobe that you aren't particularly fond of (and after reading this letter, it should be much easier to figure out which one that is).  Thanks for reading pal! /

Instead, you would realize that in order to finish the run, you would need to train your muscles and exercise until you had the strength to make it.  This concept holds true for the brain and learning, too. column127: Hey Friend, /  / How's your attitude? Is there a subject you don't like such as reading comprehension or math? /  / Well, let's pretend it's your favorite subject in school and pretend to be "gung-ho" about it. First, know that you can tackle the subject and win against it. Let's say you play a sport or an instrument. The more you practice, the better you get, right? Why? Sure, practice makes perfect, but scientifically, it's because your brain makes more neural connections that help your brain grow to adapt to the situation and better prepare you for future situations. Similarly, if you want to be better at a school subject, do practice problems. /  / Now, it's not about just any practice problems. If you're training for baseball, would you practice by shooting hoops at the basketball court? There's a difference between working hard and working smart. Analyze your situation by clearly illustrating your goals, action steps, and what strategies/resources are out there for you to reach your goal. /  / You're intelligent. Buckle up your attitude and work on difficult problems. Boost your self-esteem by solving hard problems. If you can't solve them, don't give up. Don't give up when you're halfway through a problem and feel demoralized. Just bear through it and try to think about the problem from a  different viewpoint. Maybe you'll see a different way to solve it. Hard problems make you strive to be better. Don't settle for the ordinary easy problems. /  / You can always ask your teacher for help. Surround yourself with the people you want to be like. Never settle to be a big fish in a small pond, because you'll never have room to grow. Be a small fish in a big pond and have the enthusiasm and courage to be bigger and better. /  / Good luck!

column60: If someone has a "Fixed Mindset", they don't even allow themselves the chance to learn. They believe that they can do nothing about what they know or don't know, and therefore they are choosing to be ignorant of their own possibilities. When these sorts of people "try" to "learn", they already believe they cannot learn new things and so they are not actually trying.  /  / Someone with a "Growth Mindset" at least possesses the belief that they can learn, and therefore they are more likely to learn whatever it is they are trying to accomplish.
column75: Hello friend, /  / I hear you are not doing well in school, and I believe it is probably due to the fact that you have what is called a "Fixed Mindset." A Fixed Mindset is a way of approaching learning--you believe you have a certain amount of intelligence, and if you cannot learn or do something, it simply is because of your brain capacity or intelligence. I must say that you are highly mistaken! Do not steer clear of difficult problems you cannot handle and do not shy away from asking questions when you need it. If you believe that you can learn new things, if you believe that your intelligence and your brain have endless synapses to spare, I assure you that you will most definitely learn more than you are learning now (or at least learn faster). Believing in your own intelligence and having a "Growth Mindset" allows you more room to make mistakes and learn from them. You will, consequently, stop preemptively shutting out the information that you could have easily absorbed if you hadn't done so.  /  / I hope you change your Mind about how you see the learning experience... /  / Cheers

column164: when certain aspects of your brain are damaged, your body will not be able to function like it does currently. Without your parietal lobe, you wouldn't be able to tell if you injured yourself, because the parietal lobe helps cause pain and helps your body realize when something is off balance. Without the frontal lobe, you wouldn't know when to go to class, because the frontal lobe helps you make plans. The occipital lobe helps you pick out your clothes in the morning, because it is in charge of your vision and color identification. And the temporal lobe helps you make your presentations in front of a class, because it is in charge of your speech and how you can communicate

column60: As a kid labeled precocious I had the belief that intelligence was fixed, and thus fell into the former category.  AFter wasting all those talents I came to the diametric conclusion.  But our story doesn't end there.  Because once again an idiot I attempted to become smart again, and after many years of hard work, I found out that I wasn't smart at all, no matter my assiduous application to studying sciences or languages or the arts.  So now I am rather unsure.  Types of intelligences, not merely respective to persons per se, but as in an ideal sense, I believe exist.  The easiest elucidation of this is to consider most people savants in some limited, even prosaid category.  Some people are geniuses at normal day to routine.  They do it fluently and confidently.  So take this as a limited and altogether confused parable, necessarily uninstructive because it was written by an idiot once given a golden mantle.
column75: Fized Mindset is a self fulfilling prophecy.  If you think you are as smart as you will ever be than you are just that.  If you practice, even without believing you are getting better, over time you will might be surprised to find that you in fact do get better.  Perhaps not as good as you hoped, but at least better than you thought possible, or were.
